Welcome to May's Turing-Roche newsletter! Here you can find what's new in the Turing-Roche strategic partnership and opportunities, events and news from both The Alan Turing Institute, Roche and beyond.

Our [five year partnership](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2F6iy60_Tj47UAD3RtkJvaGw&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Cc689655209544c71d21108db56bdee55%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638199146001530566%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=kJgvbIlaW1%2Fs%2B5rQ0XKCWsnsik9rI5aK4UtW5yFRciE%3D&reserved=0) was set up officially in June 2021 following a successful [Data Study Group](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2Fk_nPhmoeuqxfyq3A2YxPMQ&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Cc689655209544c71d21108db56bdee55%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638199146001530566%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=Mg2Zev5qicCzVI70Qk0nsHbzVPD4O9HgoGTVHWTQrPc%3D&reserved=0) and a 12 week research project on lung cancer treatment. Our 'North Star' is **to enable the generation of insights to better understand patient and disease heterogeneity and its relevance to clinical outcomes at an unprecedented level of precision in order to improve clinical care. 

We will be covering multiple activities over the five years to work towards our North Star, as well as building strong connections and collaborations between the Alan Turing Institute, Roche and the wider community.

If you have anything you'd like featured in a future newsletter then please get in touch with Vicky Hellon, Community Manager for the partnership at <vhellon@turing.ac.uk>

### New Preprint from our Structured Missingness Research Team

Team members from our [Structured Missingness funded project](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FuCRQaX__hT1VlPoCwrZyKw&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Cc689655209544c71d21108db56bdee55%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638199146001530566%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=8aSN5XOuJLkNhvWWQdtl4xS2g4dJDKoIEHpnlOgsHXc%3D&reserved=0), Anthony Baptista, Rubén J. Sánchez-García and Ginestra Bianconi, have published a preprint on network embedding. The process of assigning an embedding space to a network has emerged as a trend in recent decades and this review paper provides a guide to current methods and approaches from the literature. You can find the preprint [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FTJAFNtPjyiP4JGw6GSpyyw&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Cc689655209544c71d21108db56bdee55%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638199146001530566%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=7Y2I5FKHwrP6D0Nk89QnGu%2FAnA5t6W%2FAoXseo1QG56Q%3D&reserved=0).

### Partnership Senior Postdoc Chris Banerji presenting at FSHD Society International Research Conference

Chris Banerji, one of our partnership Senior Postdoctoral Research Associates, is presenting at the facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy (FSHD) Society International Research Conference in Milan in June. 

FSHD is an incurable muscular dystrophy, which is highly heterogeneous at the clinical and molecular level. Three projects on this condition, led by Chris in an international collaboration with Peter Zammit (King's College London), Baziel van Engelen (Radboud UMC) and Jeffrey Statland (Kansas UMC) have been accepted at the conference:

-   **'An in silico FSHD muscle fibre for modelling DUX4 dynamics and predicting the impact of therapy**' accepted eLife, preprint [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FpMx85zcgF9TkI3awKh5tXw&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Cc689655209544c71d21108db56bdee55%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638199146001530566%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=JZm5a%2FhG6Y6uOD8z7SmNqxdhf7OdFgvFx3zsAaO6Aks%3D&reserved=0). This work employs stochastic gene expression and compartment models to understand the heterogeneous distribution of DUX4 (a major FSHD therapeutic target) in single cell and single nuclear RNA-sequencing data from FSHD patient muscle cells. This approach led to open-source software for in silico screening of anti-DUX4 therapy in FSHD. (Cowley, Pruller...& Banerji)
-   '**FSHD muscle shows perturbation in fibroadipogenic progenitor cells, mitochondrial function and alternative splicing independently of inflammation**', under review. This multi-modal investigation combines muscle MRI, clinical and transcriptomic data from multiple tissues from FSHD patients and identifies important pathomechanisms driving disease progression. (Engquist,...,van Engelen, Zammit & Banerji)
-   '**Symptom onset and cellular pathology in facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy is accelerated by cigarette smoking**', under review. This large scale 8 year, prospective cohort study of FSHD patients in the USA identified cigarette smoking as associated with a doubling in the rate of symptom progression, a finding that was validated in cell culture models of FSHD patient muscle cells. This provides disease modifying lifestyle advice for patients in the absence of therapy. (Banerji, Heher..., Zammit & Statland)

The conference is the largest on the disease and Chris will be attending alongside PhD students Elise N. Engquist and Matthew V. Cowley who won a scholarship from the FSHD Society to attend.

### Applications open for the Turing Internship Network:*

**Deadline for applications: 07 June 2023**

Now recruiting for the 6th time since its launch in 2020, The Turing Internship Network (TIN) offers doctoral students currently enrolled in a PhD at a university in the UK or Ireland the opportunity to undertake exciting and unique 3--6-month placements at one of the Turing's business partners and collaborators. Through TIN internships students will apply their research expertise and technical skills to tackle real-world challenges and gain new skills in a business setting.

In this recruitment round TIN offers 12 paid internship opportunities in areas of research spanning from efficiency improvements for machine learning models and detection of harmful memes online to linking government data to reduce reoffending. Find out more and how to apply [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2Fn19qfBsgUEAQ6fJz6Hc_Mg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Cc689655209544c71d21108db56bdee55%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638199146001686832%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=3HJv4EiPG2dlV0T8TbYdE55N6FdNDNw2oxlltvJZ8YM%3D&reserved=0).

### Healthcare Text Analytics Conference (HealTAC)

**14-16 June 2023**

The sixth annual UK healthcare text analytics community conference will take place in Manchester. As in previous years, HealTAC 2023 brings the academic, clinical, industrial and patient communities together to discuss the current state of the art in processing healthcare free text and share experiences, results and challenges. The programme will include keynote talks, research papers, discussion panels, an industry forum, software demos, a PhD forum and poster sessions, as well as social events.

The keynotes will be delivered by Dr Angus Roberts (King's College London), with a talk "From regular expressions to pre-trained language models -- 14 years of applying NLP at the Maudsley Biomedical Research Centre" and Dr Yonghui Wu (University of Florida's College of Medicine), who will talk about "Opportunities and Challenges of Conversational Artificial Intelligence and Large Language Models in Healthcare". More information and registration [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%_X2NsZGVlPUtNZHVCaUlWNDBHU0FwX0FsN1ZMSkZWRjRRbm1CdFJWWHQzT01iNEFEcmdCQkpLNmZtUWZkVjk5S09JMTVmdEEmcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi00ZTkxYzRiOTIyMDQ0OGRiYTVmZjhjN2E5M2Q1ZjkxOSZlc2lkPTk1MTYwMjA0LWRjZjAtZWQxMS04ODQ4LTYwNDViZDBlNmJmZSJ9%2FcMu1EybEz7YGGKOenyC1nA&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Cc689655209544c71d21108db56bdee55%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638199146001686832%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=CPF7mF4qivqc796sbVT4ySh5W6sPJ5BUh8D%2F0jyZouw%3D&reserved=0).

### Turing Causal Inference Interest Group Seminar: Causal and Associational Language in Observational Health Research

**10 July 2023**

The Turing Institute's [Causal Inference Interest Group](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2F1cRixxC_mHg0VTrprBuBAw&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Cc689655209544c71d21108db56bdee55%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638199146001843077%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=x%2FfXZcIae5Vu8j2o3Yu3vfd220OsS%2FDrL5udkub%2FqwE%3D&reserved=0) monthly seminar welcomes Dr Sarah Wieten from Durham University. She will be discussing her research on which language used in the high-profile medical/public health/epidemiology literature implied causality using language linking exposures to outcomes and action recommendations; examined disconnects between language and recommendations; identified the most common linking phrases; and estimated how strongly linking phrases imply causality. Register [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FYe1mXj633PTSJICYtO8XeQ&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Cc689655209544c71d21108db56bdee55%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638199146001843077%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=NX28vC7aUrT6NiSypX8tAhQJAZG61gaStcg8dldeIK8%3D&reserved=0).

### Course: Design and Analysis of Precision Medicine Trials 

**27-28 September 2023**

Hosted by Newcastle University's Biostatistics Research Group, this two day course introduces the concept of precision medicine and covers innovative approaches. This includes novel designs (biomarker-guided, basket, umbrella, adaptive signature, adaptive enrichment designs and Sequential Multiple Assignment Randomized Trials) as well as efficient analysis approaches (e.g. Bayesian hierarchical modelling, identifying patient subgroups using high-dimensional genetic data) to help estimate sub-group specific treatment effects. ## Publication of the Month

![](https://file-eu.clickdimensions.com/turingacuk-ap7zg/files/patrick-tomasso-oaqk7qqnh_c-unsplash2.jpg)

### Tackling prediction uncertainty in machine learning for healthcare

As well as the preprint from our Structured Missingness Research team (see above!) our publication of the month for May is [this perspective paper](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%_X2NsZGVlPUtNZHVCaUlWNDBHU0FwX0FsN1ZMSkZWRjRRbm1CdFJWWHQzT01iNEFEcmdCQkpLNmZtUWZkVjk5S09JMTVmdEEmcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi00ZTkxYzRiOTIyMDQ0OGRiYTVmZjhjN2E5M2Q1ZjkxOSZlc2lkPTk1MTYwMjA0LWRjZjAtZWQxMS04ODQ4LTYwNDViZDBlNmJmZSJ9%2F599Cdnd1yBK05YEXMeyUKg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Cc689655209544c71d21108db56bdee55%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638199146001843077%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=MyoFWraGYDi38Lc3gmANr%2FqlmYTbU%2BjjP9t6GDLDuYY%3D&reserved=0) published in Nature Biomedical Engineering. From researchers based at the Department of Radiology in Massachusetts General Hospital, the publication discusses the need of prediction-uncertainty metrics in healthcare applications, with a focus on radiology. It outlines the sources of prediction uncertainty, discusses how to implement prediction-uncertainty metrics in applications that require zero tolerance to errors and in applications that are error-tolerant, and provides a concise framework for understanding prediction uncertainty in healthcare contexts.
